        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_433.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">James Ebenezer Bicheno</ref> was appointed Colonial Secretary of Van Diemen’s Land (Tasmania) in September 1842 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2063.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">DNB</hi></ref>); he probably sought information about the colony from CD.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Sir <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4272.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Saunders Sebright</ref>. In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5799.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Natural selection </hi></ref> (p. 36) CD refers to him as ‘an acute observer … who bred all sorts of animals during his whole life, &amp; who boasted that he could produce any feather in [three] years &amp; any form in [six] years’. He bred the famous Sebright bantam, in which the cocks lack male plumage (<hi rend="italic">EB,</hi> 22: 215).</note>
        </div>        
            
